<PREAMBLE>
BC-CRASH-<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">BROWN</ENAMEX>-NYT
TESTS SHOW LANDING BEACON FUNCTIONED IN <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">CROATIA</ENAMEX> CRASH
(kd)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">MATTHEW L. WALD</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">N.Y. Times News Service</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">WASHINGTON</ENAMEX>  &MD;  Officials of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Federal Aviation Administration</ENAMEX>
have tested the Croatian radio beacon that was presumably being
used by the plane carrying <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Commerce</ENAMEX> Secretary <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Ron Brown</ENAMEX> when it
crashed on approach to the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Dubrovnik</ENAMEX> airport and ``found the
landing beacon signal to be functioning properly during the
tests,'' the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Air Force</ENAMEX> said <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX>.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Air Force</ENAMEX> officials not directly involved in the investigation
also said the plane's pilot and co-pilot were very familiar with
landings using the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Dubrovnik</ENAMEX> airport's type of beacon, though
neither had landed at the airport before.
<p>
   ``We believe at this time we have the right training and the
right experience level in those aircraft,'' Lt. Gen. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Ralph E.
Eberhart</ENAMEX>, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Air Force</ENAMEX> Deputy Chief of Staff for plans and
operations, said at a briefing at the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Pentagon</ENAMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX>.
<p>
   He said that crews on aircraft used for ``distinguished
visitors'' were required to complete 52 landing approaches a year,
half with the relatively unsophisticated navigation equipment that
did not give electronic guidance on the proper descent altitude.
<p>
   Many of those training flights involve beacons like the ones at
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Dubrovnik</ENAMEX>, equipment that is common in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Eastern Europe</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   But <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Eberhart</ENAMEX> is not a member of the accident investigation
board, and he and other officials said that final conclusions would
have to come from the board.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Air Force</ENAMEX> is already moving to dispel possible criticism,
including questions about why the plane had no flight data recorder
or cockpit voice recorder, the crash-proof ``black boxes'' that
investigators rely on in most commercial crashes.
<p>
   At the briefing <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX>, Brigadier Gen. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Orin L. Godsey</ENAMEX>, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Air
Force</ENAMEX> chief of safety, said the absence of these instruments would
``complicate'' the investigation, but he added, ``Because of the
technology we have <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">today</TIMEX>, we will be able to replicate almost the
entire realm'' of information a box would have provided.
<p>
   But <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Godsey</ENAMEX> was not able to provide specifics. He said, for
example, that he did not know if AWACS, or Airborne
Warning-and-Control System, had traced the final approach of the
commerce secretary's plane, a military version of a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> 737.
<p>
   On board the plane were 27 American passengers, two Croatians
and an <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Air Force</ENAMEX> crew of six.
<p>
   The board looking into the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Dubrovnik</ENAMEX> crash has ``nearly
completed'' locating and documenting the wreckage and identifying
aircraft components, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Air Force</ENAMEX> said. But officials would not
predict when the team will return to <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Ramstein</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Germany</ENAMEX>, where
analyses will be done, or when it would report.
</TEXT>
