<PREAMBLE>
BC-<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">VALUJET</ENAMEX>-TAPE-BLOOM
AIR TRAFFIC CONTROL TOWER TAPE OF <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">VALUJET</ENAMEX> 592 REVEALS LITTLE
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Gerald Burstyn</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Bloomberg Business News</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Washington</ENAMEX>, <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">June 27</TIMEX> (<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION" STATUS="OPT">Bloomberg</ENAMEX>) -- Little light was shed on the
impending disaster that awaited <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> flight 592 in air traffic
control tower tapes released <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">today</TIMEX> by the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Federal Aviation
Administration</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   The tape covers 20 minutes of conversations between the control
tower at <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Miami</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Dade County</ENAMEX> airport and several aircraft,
including the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> flight.
<p>
   The tape confirms what investigators already knew: that
approximately six minutes into the flight, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> crew
reported trouble. ``Smoke in the cockpit, smoke in the cabin,'' the
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> crew told a flight controller in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Miami</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   Less than a minute later, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> crew requested to land at
the ``closest airport available.'' Nine seconds later, the crew
contacted the control tower for the last time.
<p>
   Fourteen minutes after flight 592 took off, the air traffic
controller asked another plane flying in the area ``how did critter
(<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ValuJet</ENAMEX> 592) make out.''
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Transportation Safety Board</ENAMEX> is currently
investigating the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">May 11</TIMEX> accident, which investigators say may have
been caused by the explosion of oxygen cylinders in the plane's
cargo hold. A preliminary report on the accident will be released
``over the next few months'' a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NTSB</ENAMEX> spokesman said.
</TEXT>
