<TEXT>
<p>
   Indeed, a plan to do so has been in the works for many months,
spurred on by intelligence warnings that the threat of terror
attacks on aircraft in the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">United States</ENAMEX> is growing, and the plan
is only being accelerated following the explosion of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> Flight
800.
<p>
   An industry advisory group formed by the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> that has been
working on security issues for more than a year formed a task force
at a meeting just hours before <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Boeing</ENAMEX> 747 exploded over
waters near <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Long Island</ENAMEX> after taking off from <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Kennedy Airport</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   Members had been told to come up with recommendations for
enhancing security and to make their report in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">October</TIMEX>. But the
vice president's commission is supposed to have preliminary
recommendations even earlier, so the two groups have been working
very closely together in recent weeks.
<p>
   Officials cautioned that the vice president's commission, which
has not yet held its first full-blown meeting, might decide to
reject the recommendations of the industry advisory group.
<p>
   The discussions between the groups shows how much tension there
is between the industry and the government over how to respond to
the growing risk of terrorism in general, especially in the wake of
the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">TWA</ENAMEX> disaster.
<p>
   Even before the cause of that disaster is explained  &MD;  and as
investigators have basically ruled out a bomb in a checked suitcase
as the explanation, since all the luggage containers on the plane
were recovered undamaged by any bomb  &MD;  the aviation industry and
the government have been negotiating over how to minimize the costs
of deploying new bomb-detecting equipment.
<p>
   The approach being pushed by industry advisory groups, with the
support of senior officials at the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> and the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">White House</ENAMEX>, would
lower the costs of the bomb detection process by instead building
up the process known as ``profiling,'' which attempts to focus
attention on certain passengers and their baggage.
<p>
   The new approach was first reported in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Saturday</TIMEX> editions of The
Washington Post, and details were confirmed by government and
industry officials.
<p>
   Already, although they may not know it, airline passengers are
profiled when they buy their tickets and when they check in for
their flights, and those who match certain criteria, some of which
are secret, are subjected to extra baggage checks.
<p>
   People whose passports are issued by nations known to support
terrorism, or people who have traveled to such countries, or people
who pay cash for one-way tickets just before a flight, would be
checked more carefully under the current profile.
<p>
   After the explosion aboard Flight 800, the profiling measures
were extended to many domestic flights.
</TEXT>
